    <main>
      <div class="ians-column">
        <h2 class="oj-pt0-important">What makes a good instructor?</h2>
        <p>Take a moment to think about the instructors that you have had in the past. Even as a qualified ATCO, you will have seen other OJTIs delivering instruction to trainees. What makes some instructors good at their job?</p>

      </div>

      <div class="oj-hero"></div>

      <div class="ians-column">
        <p>ANSPs select candidates from their pool of air traffic controllers to develop as OJTIs. The methods used to make this selection are varied but <strong>should at least recognise</strong> that:</p>
      </div>

      <div class="ians-column-wide-3 mb-12">
        <ul class="ians-grid-3 oj-selection-list list-none">
          <li>A high performing air traffic controller does not necessarily make for a competent OJTI, as they must also have the motivation and ability to build up <strong>solid learning relationships</strong>, <strong>coach</strong> and <strong>mentor</strong> trainees and be able to <strong>self-reflect</strong> on their performance as an OJTI, even in challenging circumstances.</li>
          <li>An effective OJTI should be a competent ATCO who is <strong>respected</strong> and <strong>accepted</strong> in the operational environment.</li>
          <li>A strong desire to <strong>enable</strong> others to succeed is a powerful motivator for a potential OJTI which has obvious benefits for the trainee.</li>
          <li>The ATCO has already demonstrated commitment to 
						<strong>continuous improvement</strong>. </li>
          <li>The ATCO embodies the <strong>values</strong> and <strong>learning philosophy</strong> of the organisation.</li>
          <li>Some key OJTI <strong>competencies</strong> are already evident (e.g. Collaboration, Self-Assessment).</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="ians-column">

        <p>Regulatory requirements may oblige ANSPs to select candidates who have gained a <strong>minimum</strong> number of years <strong>experience</strong> as an operational air traffic controller prior to becoming an OJTI. This can be problematic as candidates may be selected who do not have the motivators that will benefit the trainee but only themselves e.g. salary or grade enhancement.</p>

        <h2>Roles</h2>
        <p>
					Each ANSP or Training Organisation has an expectation of what roles
					their OJTI&apos;s will perform when engaged with trainees. Take a look
					at the following roles and <strong>reflect</strong> on whether your
					ANSP or Training Organisation expects you to perform all or some of
					these roles.
				</p>
      </div>

      <div class="ians-column-wide-3 mb-12">

        <section data-atabs>
          <div data-atabs-panel="default" data-atabs-tab-label="Teacher / Instructor">

            <div class="ians-grid-2">

              <div  class="oj-panel-padding">

                <p>You are expected to <strong>explain</strong> to a trainee how they should do or achieve something in the operational or simulated environment. You <strong>actively</strong> ensure that timely operational decisions are made and actions carried out as anticipated. You engage the trainee with <strong>questions or prompts</strong>.</p>

                <p>You have some basic understanding of <strong>pedagogical</strong> techniques and understand cognitive processes.</p>

              </div>

              {% image "images/roles-teacher_instructor.jpg", "A teacher talking to a student.", "oj-notched"%}
            </div>
          </div>

          <div data-atabs-panel data-atabs-tab-label="Coach">
            <div class="ians-grid-2">
              <div class="oj-panel-padding">
                <p>You are expected to <strong>support</strong> the trainee as they progress towards independent performance. You are no longer explaining how something should be done but rather guiding the trainee to <strong>work this out for themselves</strong>, formulate and carry out their own plan for the traffic, and monitor and adjust their <strong>plan independently</strong>.</p>

                <p>You can perform this coaching role with confidence because you have a clear understanding of your operational environment, and are able to predict the likely consequences and outcomes of the trainee's actions in that environment.</p>
              </div>
              {% image "images/roles-coach.jpg", "Coach and student at position.", "oj-notched" %}

            </div>
          </div>

          <div data-atabs-panel data-atabs-tab-label="Mentor">
            <div class="ians-grid-2">
              <div class="oj-panel-padding">

                <p>You are expected to encourage and support your trainees in developing positive attitudes and behaviours towards their training and integration into the team and wider professional environment.</p>
              </div>

              {% image "images/roles-mentor.jpg", "A mentor and student at position.", "oj-notched" %}
            </div>
          </div>

          <div data-atabs-panel data-atabs-tab-label="Assessor">
            <div class="ians-grid-2">

              <p class="oj-panel-padding">You <strong>evaluate the performance</strong> of your trainee to determine if the required competency standards are met. This evaluation may be in the context of formative or summative assessment.</p>

              {% image "images/roles-assessor.jpg", "An assessor observing a student.", "oj-notched" %}
            </div>
          </section>

