        <div class="ians-column">
          <h2>Competencies</h2>

          <p>
					Certain expectations can arise from the belief that an OJTI should be
					an effective teacher, human factors expert, a mentor and, at times, a
					part-time ‘psychologist&apos;. The reality is that the OJTI is very
					<strong>seldom formally educated</strong> in any of these fields and
					their expertise will come from the training and development activities
					that are provided by the ANSP.
				</p>

          <p>
					No matter which combination of roles you are expected to perform, your
					OJTI job in operational training is a challenging one, so investing
					time in developing the competencies you need is critical for your
					success as an instructor.
				</p>

          <p>
					The competencies in the
					<strong>ICAO OJTI Competency Framework</strong> have already been
					mentioned but we are now going to look at them in more detail.
				</p>

          <p>
					Bear in mind that when an organisation develops their own adapted OJTI
					competency model, they may <strong>exclude or add</strong> competencies and observable
					behaviours depending on their expectation of what roles the instructor
					will perform. Take a look at each of the competencies below to get a
					general idea of why they are relevant and which observable behaviours
					are associated with them.
				</p>
          <p class="ians-text-instruction">
					Select the competencies below to read more detail and the ICAO
					<br/>Observable behaviours. If you prefer to scroll through the same text, open the "Show competencies text" drop down below.
				</p>
